Definition 1.5. An arrow $f\colon A\to B$ in a bicategory $\mathcal{C}$ is an equivalence if there exists an arrow $f^{\prime}\colon B\to A$ together with invertible 2-cells $f\circ f^{\prime}\cong 1_{B}$ and $1_{A}\cong f^{\prime}\circ f$.
Definition 1.2. Given bicategories $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$, a pseudofunctor $F\colon\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ is given by the following data: • An assignment of objects $FC$ of $\mathcal{D}$ to each object $C$ of $\mathcal{C}$. • For all objects $A$ and $B$ of $\mathcal{C}$, a functor $F_{A,B}\colon\mathcal{C}(A,B)\to\mathcal{C}(FA,FB)$. • For all objects $A,B$ and $C$ of $\mathcal{C}$, natural isomorphisms as indicated in the following diagrams: $\displaystyle\xy{\ar^{(}.6){c}(0,15)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,B)\times\mathcal{C}(B,C)}% ;(40,15)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,C)}};{\ar_{F\times F}(0,15)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,B)\times% \mathcal{C}(B,C)};(0,0)*+{\mathcal{D}(FA,FB)\times\mathcal{D}(FB,FC)}};{\ar_{(% }.6){c}(0,0)*+{\mathcal{D}(FA,FB)\times\mathcal{D}(FB,FC)};(40,0)*+{\mathcal{D% }(FA,FC)}};{\ar^{F}(40,15)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,C)};(40,0)*+{\mathcal{D}(FA,FC)}};{% \ar@{=>}^{\varphi_{A,B,C}}(17,7.5)*+{};(23,7.5)*+{}};\endxy$ and $\displaystyle\xy{\ar^{1_{A}}(0,15)*+{1};(30,15)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,A)}};{\ar_{1_{% FA}}(0,15)*+{1};(15,0)*+{\mathcal{D}(FA,FA).}};{\ar^{F}(30,15)*+{\mathcal{C}(A% ,A)};(15,0)*+{\mathcal{D}(FA,FA).}};{\ar@{=>}^{(}.35){\upsilon_{A}}(12,7.5)*+{% };(18,7.5)*+{}};\endxy$ These data are required to be such that the following diagrams commute: $\displaystyle\xy{\ar^{\varphi*Ff}(0,15)*+{(Fh\circ Fg)\circ Ff};(30,15)*+{F(h% \circ g)\circ Ff}};{\ar^{\varphi}(30,15)*+{F(h\circ g)\circ Ff};(60,15)*+{F% \bigl{(}(h\circ g)\circ f\bigr{)}}};{\ar_{\alpha}(0,15)*+{(Fh\circ Fg)\circ Ff% };(0,0)*+{Fh\circ(Fg\circ Ff)}};{\ar_{Fh*\varphi}(0,0)*+{Fh\circ(Fg\circ Ff)};% (30,0)*+{Fh\circ F(g\circ f)}};{\ar_{\varphi}(30,0)*+{Fh\circ F(g\circ f)};(60% ,0)*+{F\bigl{(}h\circ(g\circ f)\bigr{)}}};{\ar^{F\alpha}(60,15)*+{F\bigl{(}(h% \circ g)\circ f\bigr{)}};(60,0)*+{F\bigl{(}h\circ(g\circ f)\bigr{)}}};\endxy$ $\displaystyle\xy{\ar^{(}.45){Ff*\upsilon}(0,15)*+{Ff\circ 1_{FA}};(20,15)*+{Ff% \circ F1_{A}}};{\ar^{(}.45){\varphi}(20,15)*+{Ff\circ F1_{A}};(40,15)*+{F(f% \circ 1_{A})}};{\ar_{\rho}(0,15)*+{Ff\circ 1_{FA}};(20,0)*+{Ff}};{\ar^{F\rho}(% 40,15)*+{F(f\circ 1_{A})};(20,0)*+{Ff}};\endxy\quad\text{and}\quad\xy{\ar^{% \upsilon*Ff}(0,15)*+{1_{FB}\circ Ff};(20,15)*+{F1_{B}\circ Ff}};{\ar^{(}.45){% \varphi}(20,15)*+{F1_{B}\circ Ff};(40,15)*+{F(1_{B}\circ f)}};{\ar_{\lambda}(0% ,15)*+{1_{FB}\circ Ff};(20,0)*+{Ff}};{\ar^{F\lambda}(40,15)*+{F(1_{B}\circ f)}% ;(20,0)*+{Ff}};\endxy$ for any arrows $f\colon A\to B$, $g\colon B\to C$ and $h\colon C\to D$ in $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 1.6. Given bicategories $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$, a pseudofunctor $F\colon\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ is an equivalence of bicategories if there exists a pseudofunctor $G\colon\mathcal{D}\to\mathcal{C}$ together with maps $\eta\colon 1_{\mathcal{C}}\to G\circ F$ and $\epsilon\colon F\circ G\to 1_{\mathcal{D}}$ which are equivalences in the bicategories $[\mathcal{C},\mathcal{C}]$ and $[\mathcal{D},\mathcal{D}]$, respectively.
Definition 1.3. Given pseudofunctors $F,G\colon\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$, a pseudonatural transformation $\psi\colon F\to G$ consists of the following data: • For each object $C$ of $\mathcal{C}$, an arrow $\psi_{C}\colon FC\to GC$ in $\mathcal{D}$. • For objects $A$ and $B$ of $\mathcal{C}$, a natural isomorphism $\displaystyle\xy{\ar^{F}(0,15)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,B)};(30,15)*+{\mathcal{D}(FA,FB% )}};{\ar_{G}(0,15)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,B)};(0,0)*+{\mathcal{D}(GA,GB)}};{\ar^{% \mathcal{D}(FA,\psi)}(30,15)*+{\mathcal{D}(FA,FB)};(30,0)*+{\mathcal{D}(FA,GB)% .}};{\ar_{\mathcal{D}(\psi,GB)}(0,0)*+{\mathcal{D}(GA,GB)};(30,0)*+{\mathcal{D% }(FA,GB).}};{\ar@{=>}^{\psi_{A,B}}(12,7.5)*+{};(18,7.5)*+{}};\endxy$ Note that here we are overloading the notation $\psi$. In practice this should not result in any confusion. These data are required to be such that the following diagrams commute: $\displaystyle\xy{\ar^{\alpha}(0,15)*+{(Gg\circ Gf)\circ\psi};(30,15)*+{Gg\circ% (Gf\circ\psi)}};{\ar^{Gg*\psi}(30,15)*+{Gg\circ(Gf\circ\psi)};(60,15)*+{Gg% \circ(\psi\circ Ff)}};{\ar^{\alpha^{-1}}(60,15)*+{Gg\circ(\psi\circ Ff)};(90,1% 5)*+{(Gg\circ\psi)\circ Ff}};{\ar^{\psi*Ff}(90,15)*+{(Gg\circ\psi)\circ Ff};(9% 0,0)*+{(\psi\circ Fg)\circ Ff}};{\ar_{\alpha}(90,0)*+{(\psi\circ Fg)\circ Ff};% (60,0)*+{\psi\circ(Fg\circ Ff)}};{\ar_{\psi*\varphi}(60,0)*+{\psi\circ(Fg\circ Ff% )};(30,0)*+{\psi\circ F(g\circ f)}};{\ar_{\varphi*\psi}(0,15)*+{(Gg\circ Gf)% \circ\psi};(0,0)*+{G(g\circ f)\circ\psi}};{\ar_{\psi}(0,0)*+{G(g\circ f)\circ% \psi};(30,0)*+{\psi\circ F(g\circ f)}};\endxy$ $\displaystyle\xy{\ar^{\lambda}(0,15)*+{1_{GA}\circ\psi};(30,15)*+{\psi}};{\ar^% {\rho^{-1}}(30,15)*+{\psi};(60,15)*+{\psi\circ 1_{FA}}};{\ar^{\psi*\upsilon}(6% 0,15)*+{\psi\circ 1_{FA}};(60,0)*+{\psi\circ F1_{A}.}};{\ar_{\upsilon*\psi}(0,% 15)*+{1_{GA}\circ\psi};(0,0)*+{G1_{A}\circ\psi}};{\ar_{\psi}(0,0)*+{G1_{A}% \circ\psi};(60,0)*+{\psi\circ F1_{A}.}};\endxy$
Definition 2.4. An object $A$ of $\mathcal{C}$ is fibrant when $\mathfrak{W}\pitchfork A$.
Definition 5.2. A topological prestack is a prestack $A$ such that the following conditions are satisfied: (1) The diagonal $\Delta\colon A\to A\times A$ is representable. (2) There exists a space $U$ in Top and a map $q\colon yU\to A$ such that, for all spaces $V$ in Top and maps $f\colon yV\to A$, the map $(f,q)\to V$ is an étale surjection.
Definition 1.7. A pseudofunctor $F\colon\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ is a weak equivalence of bicategories if the following conditions are satisfied: • For each object $D$ of $\mathcal{D}$, there exists an object $C$ of $\mathcal{C}$ and an equivalence $FC\to D$ in $\mathcal{D}$. • For all objects $C$ and $C^{\prime}$ of $\mathcal{C}$, the map $\mathcal{C}(C,C^{\prime})\to\mathcal{D}(FC,FC^{\prime})$ is an equivalence of categories.
Definition 3.2. A map $p\colon E\to B$ is a local fibration if and only if, for every $U$ and cover $\SS$ of $U$, the map $\displaystyle\Phi_{\SS}\colon E(U)\to\textnormal{{Desc}}(p,\SS)$ described in Section 3.4 above is a weak equivalence.
Definition 5.3. A differentiable prestack is a prestack $A$ such that there exists a manifold $U$ in Diff and a map $q\colon U\to A$ such that, for all manifolds $V$ in Diff and maps $f\colon V\to A$, the isocomma object $(f,q)$ is representable and the map $(f,q)\to V$ is an étale surjection.
Definition 1.1 (Bénabou [2]). A bicategory $\mathcal{C}$ consists of a collection of objects $A,B,\ldots$ together with the following data: • Categories $\mathcal{C}(A,B)$ for objects $A$ and $B$ of $\mathcal{C}$. The objects of $\mathcal{C}(A,B)$ are called arrows and the arrows are called 2-cells. When $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are composable 2-cells in $\mathcal{C}(A,B)$ we denote their composite by $\beta\cdot\alpha$. • For objects $A,B$ and $C$ of $\mathcal{C}$, a functor $c_{A,B,C}:\mathcal{C}(A,B)\times\mathcal{C}(B,C)\to\mathcal{C}(A,C)$. We denote $c_{A,B,C}(f,g)$ by $g\circ f$, for arrows $f\in\mathcal{C}(A,B)$ and $g\in\mathcal{C}(B,C)$, and we denote $c_{A,B,C}(\alpha,\beta)$ by $\beta*\alpha$, for 2-cells $\beta\in\mathcal{C}(A,B)$ and $\alpha\in\mathcal{C}(B,C)$. When no confusion will result we omit the subscripts and write $c$ instead of $c_{A,B,C}$. • For each object $A$ of $\mathcal{C}$, an arrow $1_{A}\in\mathcal{C}(A,A)$. • For objects $A,B,C$ and $D$ of $\mathcal{C}$, a natural isomorphism: $\displaystyle\xy{\ar^{(}.55){c\times\mathcal{C}(C,D)}(0,15)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,B)% \times\mathcal{C}(B,C)\times\mathcal{C}(C,D)};(50,15)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,C)\times% \mathcal{C}(C,D)}};{\ar_{\mathcal{C}(A,B)\times c}(0,15)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,B)% \times\mathcal{C}(B,C)\times\mathcal{C}(C,D)};(0,0)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,B)\times% \mathcal{C}(B,D)}};{\ar_{c}(0,0)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,B)\times\mathcal{C}(B,D)};(50% ,0)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,D).}};{\ar^{c}(50,15)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,C)\times\mathcal{C}(% C,D)};(50,0)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,D).}};{\ar@{=>}^{\alpha_{A,B,C,D}}(22,7.5)*+{};(2% 8,7.5)*+{}};\endxy$ As with the composition functors $c$, we will omit subscripts and write $\alpha$ instead of $\alpha_{A,B,C,D}$. • For objects $A$ and $B$ of $\mathcal{C}$, natural isomorphisms $\lambda_{A,B}$ and $\rho_{A,B}$ as indicated in the following diagrams: $\displaystyle\xy{\ar^{(}.4){1_{A}\times\mathcal{C}(A,B)}(0,15)*+{1\times% \mathcal{C}(A,B)};(36,15)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,A)\times\mathcal{C}(A,B)}};{\ar_{\pi% _{1}}(0,15)*+{1\times\mathcal{C}(A,B)};(18,0)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,B)}};{\ar^{c}(36% ,15)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,A)\times\mathcal{C}(A,B)};(18,0)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,B)}};{% \ar@{<=}^{\rho_{A,B}}(15,7.5)*+{};(21,7.5)*+{}};\endxy\quad\xy{\ar^{(}.4){% \mathcal{C}(A,B)\times 1_{B}}(0,15)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,B)\times 1};(36,15)*+{% \mathcal{C}(A,B)\times\mathcal{C}(B,B)}};{\ar_{\pi_{0}}(0,15)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,% B)\times 1};(18,0)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,B).}};{\ar^{c}(36,15)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,B)% \times\mathcal{C}(B,B)};(18,0)*+{\mathcal{C}(A,B).}};{\ar@{<=}^{\lambda_{A,B}}% (15,7.5)*+{};(21,7.5)*+{}};\endxy$ We again omit subscripts and simply write $\lambda$ and $\rho$. These data are required to satisfy the following conditions: • Given $f\in\mathcal{C}(A,B)$, $g\in\mathcal{C}(B,C)$, $h\in\mathcal{C}(C,D)$ and $k\in\mathcal{C}(D,E)$, the following diagram commutes: $\displaystyle\xy{\ar^{\alpha*f}(0,15)*+{\bigl{(}(k\circ h)\circ g\bigr{)}\circ f% };(60,15)*+{\bigl{(}k\circ(h\circ g)\bigr{)}\circ f}};{\ar_{\alpha}(0,15)*+{% \bigl{(}(k\circ h)\circ g\bigr{)}\circ f};(0,0)*+{(k\circ h)\circ(g\circ f)}};% {\ar_{\alpha}(0,0)*+{(k\circ h)\circ(g\circ f)};(30,0)*+{k\circ\bigl{(}h\circ(% g\circ f)\bigr{)}}};{\ar^{\alpha}(60,15)*+{\bigl{(}k\circ(h\circ g)\bigr{)}% \circ f};(60,0)*+{k\circ\bigl{(}(h\circ g)\circ f\bigr{)}.}};{\ar^{k*\alpha}(6% 0,0)*+{k\circ\bigl{(}(h\circ g)\circ f\bigr{)}.};(30,0)*+{k\circ\bigl{(}h\circ% (g\circ f)\bigr{)}}};\endxy$ • Given $f\in\mathcal{C}(A,B)$ and $g\in\mathcal{C}(B,C)$, the following diagram commutes: $\displaystyle\xy{\ar^{\alpha}(0,15)*+{(g\circ 1_{B})\circ f};(30,15)*+{g\circ(% 1_{B}\circ f)}};{\ar_{\rho*f}(0,15)*+{(g\circ 1_{B})\circ f};(15,0)*+{g\circ f% .}};{\ar^{g*\lambda}(30,15)*+{g\circ(1_{B}\circ f)};(15,0)*+{g\circ f.}};\endxy$
Definition 4.4. Given maps $f\colon A\to B$ and $g\colon C\to B$ in $\textnormal{{PreSt}}(\mathcal{C})$, the isocomma object $(f,g)$ is the pseudofunctor given at $U$ by the category $(f,g)(U)$ with Objects: Tuples consisting of objects $a$ and $c$ of $A(U)$ and $C(U)$, respectively, and an isomorphism $\xi\colon f(a)\cong g(c)$. Arrows: An arrow $(a,c,\xi)\to(b,d,\zeta)$ is given by maps $i\colon a\to b$ and $j\colon c\to d$ such that the diagram $\displaystyle\xy{\ar^{f(i)}(0,15)*+{f(a)};(20,15)*+{f(b)}};{\ar_{\xi}(0,15)*+{% f(a)};(0,0)*+{g(c)}};{\ar_{g(j)}(0,0)*+{g(c)};(20,0)*+{g(d)}};{\ar^{\zeta}(20,% 15)*+{f(b)};(20,0)*+{g(d)}};\endxy$ commutes. The action of $(f,g)$ on arrows is simply by restriction of all of the aforementioned data.
Definition 2.2. A system of fibrant objects on a bicategory $\mathcal{C}$ consists of a collection of maps $\mathfrak{W}$ (weak equivalences) of $\mathcal{C}$ together with a pseudofunctor $Q\colon\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{C}$ (fibrant replacement) and a pseudonatural transformation $\eta\colon 1_{\mathcal{C}}\to Q$ such that the following axioms are satisfied: Identities: All identity arrows $1_{A}\colon A\to A$ are in $\mathfrak{W}$. 3-for-2: Given a diagram $\displaystyle\xy{\ar^{f}(0,0)*+{A};(24,0)*+{C}};{\ar_{g}(0,0)*+{A};(12,-14)*+{% B}};{\ar_{h}(12,-14)*+{B};(24,0)*+{C}};{\ar@{=>}^{\gamma}(12,-3)*+{};(12,-8)*+% {}};\endxy$ with $\gamma$ an isomorphism, if any two of $f,g$ and $h$ are weak equivalences, then so is the third. Fibrant Replacement: The components of $\eta$ are weak equivalences and $\mathfrak{W}\pitchfork Q(A)$ for any object $A$ of $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 4.1. A map $h\colon A\to B$ in $\textnormal{{PreSt}}(\mathcal{C})$ is said to be locally essentially surjective on objects if and only if for any $U$ and $b\in B(U)$ there exists a cover $\SS=(f_{\alpha}\colon U_{\alpha}\to U)$ of $U$ together with, for each $\alpha$, an element $\tilde{b}_{\alpha}\in A(U_{\alpha})$ and an isomorphism $\psi_{\alpha}\colon h(\tilde{b}_{\alpha})\to b|_{\alpha}$.
Definition 5.3. The theory of parallels ${\mathbb{P}}(D)$ for a pasting diagram $D$ is the essentially algebraic theory with the same types and object valued operations as ${\mathbb{T}}(D)$ and with arrow-valued operations given by all set functions $\pi$ with the same domain and codomain as the instantiation of an arrow-valued operation $\omega$ of ${\mathbb{T}}(D)$ in the tautologous model and satisfying $s(\pi)=s(\omega)$ and $t(\pi)=t(\omega)$ (we call $\pi$ a parallel for $\omega$), and all equations that hold among (iterated generalized) compositions of these functions as axioms.
Definition 5.9. For any well-formed labeling of a whiskered polygon $W$, $\mathbb{O}$ the set of operations occuring in the replacement labelings of both paths, and $\mathbb{O}_{n}$ a family of parallels for $\mathbb{O}$, let $f_{1},\ldots,f_{k}$ (resp. $g_{1},\ldots,g_{\ell}$) be the replacement labeling on the maximal path which traverses domain (resp. codomain) of the 2-cell. The cocycle-type condition associated to $W$ is the equation $\sum_{\stackrel{{\scriptstyle i_{1},\ldots,i_{k}\in\{0,1\}}}{{i_{1}+\ldots+i_{% k}=1}}}f_{1}^{(i_{1})},f_{2}^{(i_{2})},\ldots,f_{n}^{(i_{k})}-\sum_{\stackrel{% {\scriptstyle j_{1},\ldots,j_{\ell}\in\{0,1\}}}{{j_{1}+\ldots+j_{\ell}=1}}}g_{% 1}^{(j_{1})},g_{2}^{(j_{2})},\ldots,g_{\ell}^{(j_{\ell})}=0.$ The $m^{th}$ order obstruction-type expression associated to $W$ is the expression $\sum_{\stackrel{{\scriptstyle i_{1},\ldots,i_{k}\in\{0,\ldots,m-1\}}}{{i_{1}+% \ldots+i_{k}=m}}}f_{1}^{(i_{1})},f_{2}^{(i_{2})},\ldots,f_{n}^{(i_{k})}-\sum_{% \stackrel{{\scriptstyle j_{1},\ldots,j_{\ell}\in\{0,\ldots,m-1\}}}{{j_{1}+% \ldots+j_{\ell}=m}}}g_{1}^{(j_{1})},g_{2}^{(j_{2})},\ldots,g_{\ell}^{(j_{\ell}% )}.$ And, the $m^{th}$ order cobounding-type condition associated to $W$ is the expression $\sum_{\stackrel{{\scriptstyle i_{1},\ldots,i_{k}\in\{0,\ldots,m\}}}{{i_{1}+% \ldots+i_{k}=m}}}f_{1}^{(i_{1})},f_{2}^{(i_{2})},\ldots,f_{n}^{(i_{k})}-\sum_{% \stackrel{{\scriptstyle j_{1},\ldots,j_{\ell}\in\{0,\ldots,m\}}}{{j_{1}+\ldots% +j_{\ell}=m}}}g_{1}^{(j_{1})},g_{2}^{(j_{2})},\ldots,g_{\ell}^{(j_{\ell})}=0.$
Definition 5.15. If $D$ is a $k$-linear pasting diagram, ${\mathbb{T}}(D)$ its theory, or an extension thereof with the same types, its deformation theory is polygonizable if the cochain group in which cocycles specify first order deformations admits a direct sum decomposition indexed a family of equational axioms of the theory each of which can be expressed as the vanishing of the difference of the values of the paths in a well-formed labeling of a directed polygon (we call such a polygon equipped with its well-formed labeling an axiomatic polygon), and which, moreover satisfy P1 The vanishing of each direct summand of the cocycle is precisely the cocycle-type condition associated to the axiomatic polygon indexing the direct summand. P2 Each direct summand of the $m^{th}$ order obstruction is the obsturuction-type expression associated to the axiomatic polygon indexing the direct summand. P3 The cobounding condition for the extension of a deformation to the next degree is the direct sum of the cobounding-type conditions associated to the axiomatic polygons. P4 And the coboundary of an obstruction admits a direct sum decomposition in which each direct summand is a signed sum of expressions specified by labeling whiskered polygons with the polygon labeled by the obstruction, and the whiskers labeled by operations of ${\mathbb{T}}(D)$ (degree 0 labels in the system of parallels naming the deformation terms).
Definition 5.1. A directed polygon $P$ is a 2-computad with a single 2-cell, all of whose 0- and 1-cells lie in the boundary of the 2-cell. A whiskered polygon $W$ is a 2-computad with a single 2-cell $P$, whose underlying 1-computad is the union of two 1-dimensional pasting schemes (directed paths), with the same 0-domain and 0-codomain, whose underlying cell complex is contractible. We refer to the 1-dimensional pasting scheme consisting of the path from the 0-domain of $W$ to the 0-domain of $P$ as the domain whisker (note: it may be simply a 0-cell), and the 1-dimensional pasting scheme consisting of the path from the 0-codomain of $P$ to the 0-codomain of $W$ as the codomain whisker (again it may simply be a 0-cell). A tiled sphere is a 3-computad with a single 3-cell, all of whose 0-, 1- and 2-cells lie in the boundary of the 3-cell.
Definition 5.6. A well-formed labeling of a whiskered polygon (resp. tiled sphere) is an assignment $e\mapsto\lambda_{e}$ to each directed 1-cell of arrow-valued wff in ${\mathbb{T}}(D)$ for some pasting diagram (or an appropriate extension of this theory) with the properties WF0 Edges are not labeled with variables (i.e. all labels involve an operation in the theory). WF1 For each 1-pasting scheme (directed path) $e_{1},e_{2},\ldots e_{n}$ from the 0-domain of the whiskered polygon (resp. tiled sphere) the labels $\lambda_{e_{1}},\ldots,\lambda_{e_{n}}$ can be iteratively replaced, beginning at the 0-codomain, with labels $\tilde{\lambda}_{e_{1}},\ldots,\tilde{\lambda}_{e_{n}}$ such that WF1a If the only proper wfss of $\lambda_{e_{i}}$ are variables then $\tilde{\lambda}_{e_{i}}=\lambda_{e_{i}}$. WF1b For all $i$ $\tilde{\lambda}_{e_{i}}$ is equivalent to $\lambda_{e_{i}}$. WF1c In the list of replacement labels $\tilde{\lambda}_{e_{1}},\ldots,\tilde{\lambda}_{e_{n}}$, for each $\tilde{\lambda}_{e_{i}}$, if $\kappa$ is a wff occuring $m$ times as a non-minimal wfs of $\tilde{\lambda}_{e_{i}}$, then there exist $m$ distinct $j$’s with $j<i$ such that $\tilde{\lambda}_{e_{j}}=\kappa$. WF2 If $e_{1},e_{2},\ldots e_{n}$ is a maximal directed path in a whiskered polygon (resp. tiled sphere), the replacement labels $\tilde{\lambda}_{e_{1}},\ldots,\tilde{\lambda}_{e_{n}}$ are precisely the non-minimal wfss of $\tilde{\lambda}_{e_{n}}$. WF3 For every 2-cell, and every maximal extension of the 2-cell to a whiskered polygon, the labels of the final edges of the two paths from the 0-domain to the 0-codomain of the whiskered polygon are equivalents. (Note this condition is vacuously true unless the 0-codomain of the 2-cell is the 0-codomain of the whiskered polygon.)
Definition 7.1. A pasting diagram is finely divided if every 2-cell is either a bigon or a triangle labeled with the identity natural transformation, and every 3-cell is of one of the following forms: • a composition-free pillow with bigonal cross-section (imposing the equality of two natural transformations between the same pair of functors) • a diagram of the form in Proposition 6.5 or its 2-dual • a ”triangular pillow” as in Example 3.1 • a diagram of the form in Example 3.6 • a diagram of the form in Proposition 6.6 • a diagram of the form in Example 3.7 • a diagram of the form in Proposition 6.7
Definition 5.4. An equivalent of a wff is any wff of the same type in the same variables such that for every instantiation of the variables in the two formulas, the values are equal.
Definition 5.11. Given a well-formed labeling of a whiskered polygon $W$ with 2-cell $P$, let $\mathbb{O}$ be the set of operations occuring in the replacement labelings of both paths, and $\mathbb{O}_{n}$ a family of parallels for $\mathbb{O}$. Recall that ${\mathbb{P}}(W)$ is the theory of parallels for $W$ (and thus includes the elements of $\mathbb{O}_{n}$. Let $s$ and $(D,\leq)$ be as in the discussion above. And suppose the last $t$ edges of each path lie in the codomain whisker. The $m^{th}$ order strong vanishing condition associated to $W$ (for $m\geq 0$) is the condition that $\displaystyle\forall\Phi_{1},\ldots\Phi_{t}\sum_{\stackrel{{\scriptstyle i_{s+% 1},\ldots,i_{k-t}\in\{0,\ldots,m\}}}{{i_{s+1}+\ldots+i_{k-t}=m}}}\hat{f}_{s+1}% ^{(i_{s+1})},\hat{f}_{s+2}^{(i_{s+2})},\ldots,\hat{f}_{k-t}^{(i_{k-t})},\Phi_{% 1},\ldots\Phi_{t}-$ $\displaystyle\sum_{\stackrel{{\scriptstyle j_{s+1},\ldots,j_{\ell-t}\in\{0,% \ldots,m\}}}{{j_{s+1}+\ldots+j_{\ell-t}=m}}}\hat{g}_{s+1}^{(j_{s+1})},\hat{g}_% {s+2}^{(j_{s+2})},\ldots,\hat{g}_{\ell-t}^{(j_{\ell-t})},\Phi_{1},\ldots\Phi_{t}$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle 0.$ where the hatting of wffs indicates the result of the following process: for each maximal element of $(D,\leq)$ select a variable of the same type which does not occur in among the variables used in the labeling; the hatted wff is the result of replacing all wfss in that equivalence class with the corresponding variable; and the universal quantification ranges over all parallels in ${\mathbb{P}}(W)$ to the labels on the corresponding edge of the codomain whisker.
Definition 5.2. To any pasting diagram $D$, theory of $D$, ${\mathbb{T}}(D)$, is the essentially algebraic theory with types $O_{\cal C}$ and $A_{\cal C}$ for each category $\cal C$ in the diagram (the objects of $\cal C$ and the arrows of $\cal C$ respectively) and operations • $Id_{\cal C}(-)$ of arity $O_{\cal C}$ and type $A_{\cal C}$, • $s_{\cal C}$ and $t_{\cal C}$ of arity $A_{\cal C}$ and type $O_{\cal C}$, and • $m_{\cal C}$ of arity $A_{{\cal C}\;t}\!\!\times_{s}A_{\cal C}$ and type $A_{\cal C}$ for each category $\cal C$ in $D$; • $F_{O}$ of arity $O_{\cal C}$ and type $O_{\cal D}$ and • $F_{A}$ of arity $A_{\cal C}$ and type $A_{\cal D}$ for each functor $F:\cal C\rightarrow\cal D$ in $D$; and • $\sigma$ of arity $O_{\cal C}$ and type $A_{\cal D}$ for each natural transformation $\sigma:F\Rightarrow G$ for $F,G:\cal C\rightarrow\cal D$ in $D$. And, with axioms the equations expressing the axioms of categories for each 6-tuple $(O_{\cal C},A_{\cal C},Id_{\cal C},s_{\cal C},t_{\cal C},m_{\cal C})$, the functoriality of each $(F_{O},F_{A})$ and the naturality of each $\sigma$.
Definition 5.8. Consider any set of arrow-valued operations $\mathbb{O}$ in ${\mathbb{T}}(D)$ for some $D$. Fix $n\in\mathbb{N}\cup\{\infty\}$. To each arrow-valued operation $\psi\in\mathbb{O}$ associate a sequence of parallels $\psi^{(k)}$ in the sense of Definition 5.3 (truncated at $k=n$ if $n<\infty$) with $\psi^{(0)}=\psi$. We call $\psi^{(k)}$ the degree $k$ parallel of $\psi$, and a choice $\mathbb{O}_{n}$ of such a sequence for every operation in $\mathbb{O}$, a degree $n$ family of parallels for $\mathbb{O}$
Definition 3.2. Let $T$ be a finite nonempty set, let $I$ be a finite poset, let $J$ be a lower subset of $I$. Let $\vec{A}^{t}=(A^{t}_{i},f^{t}_{i,j}\mid i\leq j\text{ in }I)$ be a diagram of algebras for all $t\in T$, such that $\vec{A}^{s}\mathbin{\restriction}J=\vec{A}^{t}\mathbin{\restriction}J$ for all $s,t\in T$, that is (1) The equality $A^{s}_{j}=A^{t}_{j}$ holds for all $s,t\in T$ and all $j\in J$. (2) The equality $f^{s}_{i,j}=f^{t}_{i,j}$ holds for all $s,t\in T$ and all $i\leq j$ in $J$. Set $A_{i}=\begin{cases}A_{i}^{t}&\text{for any $t\in T$, if $i\in J$}\\ \prod_{t\in T}A_{i}^{t}&\text{if $i\in I-J$}\end{cases},\quad\text{for each $i% \in I$}$ If $i\in J$, denote $\pi_{i}^{t}=\mathrm{id}_{A_{i}}=\mathrm{id}_{A_{i}^{t}}$. If $i\in I-J$, denote $\pi_{i}^{t}\colon A_{i}\to A_{i}^{t}$ the canonical projection. Let $\displaystyle f_{i,j}\colon A_{i}$ $\displaystyle\to A_{j}$ $\displaystyle x$ $\displaystyle\mapsto\begin{cases}f_{i,j}^{t}(x)&\text{for any $t\in T$, if $i,% j\in J$}\\ (f_{i,j}^{t}(x))_{t\in T}&\text{if $i\in J$ and $j\in I-J$}\\ (f_{i,j}^{t}(x_{t}))_{t\in T}&\text{if $i,j\in I-J$ and $x=(x_{t})_{t\in T}$}% \\ \end{cases},\quad\text{for all $i\leq j$ in~{}$I$}$ Then $\vec{A}=(A_{i},f_{i,j}\mid i\leq j\text{ in~{}$I$})$ is the product of $(\vec{A}^{t})_{t\in T}$ over $J$, and $\vec{\pi}^{t}=(\pi_{i}^{t})_{i\in I}\colon\vec{A}\to\vec{A}^{t}$ is the canonical projection.
Definition 3.9. Let $L$ be a nontrivial bounded lattice, let $\mathcal{C}$ be a set of spanning finite chains of $L$. Set $A_{\emptyset}=\{0,1\}$, set $A_{\top}=L$, and let $A_{P}$ be the sublattice of $L$ generated by $\bigcup_{C\in P}C$ for each $P\in\mathcal{I}(\mathcal{C})-\{\emptyset,\top\}$. Let $f_{P,Q}\colon A_{P}\to A_{Q}$ be the inclusion map, for all $P\leq Q$ in $\mathcal{I}(\mathcal{C})$. Then $\vec{A}=(A_{P},f_{P,Q}\mid P\leq Q\text{ in }\mathcal{I}(\mathcal{C}))$ is the $\mathcal{C}$-chain diagram of $L$. Let $K$ be a spanning partial sublattice of $L$. We denote by $\mathcal{C}_{K}$ be the set of all spanning chains of $K$ of length either $2$ or $3$. The chain diagram of $K$ in $L$ is the $\mathcal{C}_{K}$-chain diagram of $L$.
Definition 3.6. Let $\boldsymbol{B}$ be a gamp of lattices such that $\widetilde{B}$ is a finite Boolean lattice. A chain $x_{0}<x_{1}<\dots<x_{n}$ of $\boldsymbol{B}$ is a congruence chain of $\boldsymbol{B}$ if there exists a bijection $\sigma\colon n\to\operatorname{At}\widetilde{B}$ such that $\delta_{\boldsymbol{B}}(x_{k},x_{k+1})=\sigma(k)$ for each $k<n$. Let $C=\{c_{0},\dots,c_{n}\}$ be a chain with $c_{0}<c_{1}<\dots<c_{n}$ and let $\xi\colon\widetilde{B}\to\operatorname{Con}_{\mathrm{c}}C$ be an isomorphism. A congruence chain $x_{0}<\dots<x_{n}$ of $\boldsymbol{B}$ is direct for $(\xi,C)$ if $\xi(\delta_{\boldsymbol{B}}(x_{k},x_{k+1}))=\Theta_{C}(c_{k},c_{k+1})$ for all $k<n$. We simply say that $x_{0}<x_{1}<\dots<x_{n}$ is a direct congruence chain of $\boldsymbol{B}$ in case $\xi$ and $C$ are both understood. In both cases $x_{0}$ and $x_{n}$ are the extremities of the congruence chain. Given a lattice $B$ with a finite Boolean congruence lattice, a congruence chain of $B$ is a congruence chain of $\boldsymbol{G}(B)$.
Definition 2.1. Let $(A,\ast)$ be a ${\bf k}$-algebra with multiplication $\ast$. (a) Let $(R,\circ)$ be a ${\bf k}$-algebra with multiplication $\circ$. Let $\ell,r:A\rightarrow{\rm End}_{\bf k}(R)$ be two linear maps. We call $(R,\circ,\ell,r)$ or simply $R$ an $A$-bimodule ${\bf k}$-algebra if $(R,\ell,r)$ is an $A$-bimodule that is compatible with the multiplication $\circ$ on $R$. More precisely, we have $\displaystyle\ell(x\ast y)v$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\ell(x)(\ell(y)v),\;\ell(x)(v\circ w)=(\ell(x)v)\circ w,$ $\displaystyle vr(x\ast y)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle(vr(x))r(y),\;(v\circ w)r(x)=v\circ(wr(x)),$ $\displaystyle(\ell(x)v)r(y)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\ell(x)(vr(y)),\;(vr(x))\circ w=v\circ(\ell(x)w),\;\forall\;x,y% \in A,v,w\in R.$ (b) A homomorphism between two $A$-bimodule ${\bf k}$-algebras $(R_{1},\circ_{1},\ell_{1},r_{1})$ and $(R_{2},\circ_{2},\ell_{2},r_{2})$ is a ${\bf k}$-linear map $g:R_{1}\to R_{2}$ that is both an $A$-bimodule homomorphism and a ${\bf k}$-algebra homomorphism.
Definition 3.2. Let $(A,\ast)$ be a ${\bf k}$-algebra. (a) Let $\mathbf{IO}^{\rm alg}_{\lambda}(A,\ast)$ (resp. $\mathbf{IO}^{\rm mod}(A,\ast)$) denote the set of invertible (i.e., bijective) ${\mathcal{O}}$-operators $\alpha:R\to A$ on the algebra of weight $\lambda\in{\bf k}$ (resp. on the module), where $R=(R,\circ,\ell,r)$ is an $A$-bimodule ${\bf k}$-algebra (resp. $R=(R,\ell,r)$ is an $A$-module). (b) Let ${\bf DT}(A,\ast)$ $($resp. ${\bf DD}(A,\ast)$$)$ denote the set of dendriform trialgebra $($resp. dialgebra$)$ structures $(A,\prec,\succ,\cdot)$ $($resp. $(A,\prec,\succ)$$)$ on $(A,\ast)$ such that $\ast=\prec+\succ+\;\cdot$ $($resp. $\ast=\prec+\succ$$)$. (c) Let $\Psi^{\rm alg}_{A}:\mathbf{IO}^{\rm alg}(A,\ast)\longrightarrow{\bf DT}(A,\ast% ),\quad\alpha\mapsto(\prec_{\alpha,A},\succ_{\alpha,A},\cdot_{\alpha,A})$ $(resp.\quad\Psi^{\rm mod}_{A}:\mathbf{IO}^{\rm mod}(A,\ast)\longrightarrow{\bf DD% }(A,\ast),\quad\alpha\mapsto(\prec_{\alpha,A},\succ_{\alpha,A}).)$ be the maps defined by Proposition 3.1.
Definition 2.5. ([25]) Let ${\bf k}$ be a commutative ring. A dendriform ${\bf k}$-trialgebra is a quadruple $(T,\prec,\succ,\cdot)$ consisting of a ${\bf k}$-module $T$ and three bilinear products $\prec$, $\succ$ and $\cdot$ such that $\displaystyle(x\prec y)\prec z=x\prec(y\star z),\ (x\succ y)\prec z=x\succ(y% \prec z),$ $\displaystyle(x\star y)\succ z=x\succ(y\succ z),\ (x\succ y)\cdot z=x\succ(y% \cdot z),$ $\displaystyle(x\prec y)\cdot z=x\cdot(y\succ z),\ (x\cdot y)\prec z=x\cdot(y% \prec z),\ (x\cdot y)\cdot z=x\cdot(y\cdot z)$ for all $x,y,z\in T$. Here $\star=\prec+\succ+\cdot.$
Definition 1.1. Let $R$ be a ${\bf k}$-algebra and let $\lambda\in{\bf k}$ be given. If a ${\bf k}$-linear map $P:R\rightarrow R$ satisfies the Rota-Baxter relation: $P(x)P(y)=P(P(x)y)+P(xP(y))+\lambda P(xy),\quad\forall x,y\in R,$ then $P$ is called a Rota-Baxter operator of weight $\lambda$ and $(R,P)$ is called a Rota-Baxter algebra of weight $\lambda$.
Definition 1.2. A dendriform dialgebra is a triple $(R,\prec,\succ)$ consisting of a ${\bf k}$-module $R$ and two bilinear operations $\prec$ and $\succ$ on $R$ such that $(x\prec y)\prec z=x\prec(y\star z),\;\;(x\succ y)\prec z=x\succ(y\prec z),\;\;% x\succ(y\succ z)=(x\star y)\succ z,$ for all $x,y,z\in R$. Here $x\star y=x\prec y+x\succ y$.
Definition 2.2. Let $(A,\ast)$ be a ${\bf k}$-algebra. (a) Let $V$ be an $A$-bimodule. A linear map $\alpha:V\rightarrow A$ is called an ${\mathcal{O}}$-operator on the module $V$ if $\alpha$ satisfies $\alpha(u)\ast\alpha(v)=\alpha(\ell(\alpha(u)v))+\alpha(ur(\alpha(v))),\;\;% \forall u,v\in V.$ (b) Let $(R,\circ,\ell,r)$ be an $A$-bimodule ${\bf k}$-algebra and $\lambda\in{\bf k}$. A linear map $\alpha:R\rightarrow A$ is called an ${\mathcal{O}}$-operator on the algebra $R$ of weight $\lambda$ if $\alpha$ satisfies $\alpha(u)\ast\alpha(v)=\alpha(\ell(\alpha(u)v))+\alpha(ur(\alpha(v)))+\lambda% \alpha(u\circ v),\;\;\forall u,v\in R.$
Definition 3.4. Let $(A,\ast)$ be a ${\bf k}$-algebra. (a) For $A$-bimodule ${\bf k}$-algebras $(R_{i},\circ_{i},\ell_{i},r_{i})$ and invertible ${\mathcal{O}}$-operators $\alpha_{i}:R_{i}\to A,i=1,2,$ call $\alpha_{1}$ and $\alpha_{2}$ isomorphic, denoted by $\alpha_{1}\cong\alpha_{2}$, if there is an isomorphism $g:(R_{1},\circ_{1},\ell_{1},r_{1})\to(R_{2},\circ_{2},\ell_{2},r_{2})$ of $A$-bimodule ${\bf k}$-algebras (see Definition 2.1) such that $\alpha_{1}=\alpha_{2}g$. Similarly define isomorphic invertible ${\mathcal{O}}$-operators on modules. (b) For $A$-bimodule ${\bf k}$-algebras $(R_{i},\circ_{i},\ell_{i},r_{i})$ and invertible ${\mathcal{O}}$-operators $\alpha_{i}:R_{i}\to A,i=1,2,$ call $\alpha_{1}$ and $\alpha_{2}$ equivalent, denoted by $\alpha_{1}\sim\alpha_{2}$, if there exists a ${\bf k}$-algebra automorphism $f:A\to A$ such that $f\alpha_{1}\cong\alpha_{2}$. In other words, if there exist a ${\bf k}$-algebra automorphism $f:A\to A$ and an isomorphism $g:(R_{1},\circ_{1},\ell_{1}f^{-1},r_{1}f^{-1})\to(R_{2},\circ_{2},\ell_{2},r_{% 2})$ of $A$-bimodule ${\bf k}$-algebras such that $f\alpha_{1}=\alpha_{2}g$. Similar define equivalent invertible ${\mathcal{O}}$-operators on modules. (c) Let $\mathbf{IO}^{\rm alg}(A,\ast)/{\cong}$ $($resp. $\mathbf{IO}^{\rm alg}(A,\ast)/{\sim}$$)$ denote the set of equivalent classes from the relation $\cong$ $($resp. $\sim$$)$. Similarly define $\mathbf{IO}^{\rm mod}(A,\ast)/{\cong}$ and $\mathbf{IO}^{\rm mod}(A,\ast)/\sim$. (d) Two dendriform trialgebras $(A,\prec_{i},\succ_{i},\cdot_{i}),i=1,2,$ on $A$ are called isomorphic, denoted by $(A,\prec_{1},\succ_{1},\cdot_{1})\cong(A,\prec_{2},\succ_{2},\cdot_{2})$ if there is a linear bijection $F:A\to A$ such that $F(x\prec_{1}y)=F(x)\prec_{2}F(y),\quad F(x\succ_{1}y)=F(x)\succ_{2}F(y),\quad F% (x\cdot_{1}y)=F(x)\cdot_{2}F(y),\quad\forall x,y\in A.$ (e) Two dendriform dialgebras $(A,\prec_{i},\succ_{i}),i=1,2,$ on $A$ are called isomorphic, denoted by $(A,\prec_{1},\succ_{1})\cong(A,\prec_{2},\succ_{2})$ if there is a linear bijection $F:A\to A$ such that $F(x\prec_{1}y)=F(x)\prec_{2}F(y),\quad F(x\succ_{1}y)=F(x)\succ_{2}F(y),\quad% \forall x,y\in A.$ (f) Let ${\bf DT}(A,\ast)/\cong$ $($resp. ${\bf DD}(A,\ast)/\cong$$)$ denote the set of equivalent classes of ${\bf DT}(A,\ast)$ $($resp. ${\bf DD}(A,\ast)$$)$ modulo the isomorphisms.
Definition 24 A partial Rickart C*-algebra $A$ is a partial AW*-algebra, if it comes equipped with an operation $\bigvee\colon\{X\subseteq\mathrm{Proj}(A)\mid X\times X\subseteq\odot\}\to% \mathrm{Proj}(A),$ in such a way that each pairwise commeasurable $S\subseteq A$ is contained in a pairwise commeasurable $T\subseteq A$ on which the operations determine a commutative AW*-algebra structure (i.e. the structure is that of a commutative Rickart C*-algebra, whose projections form a complete Boolean algebra with suprema given by the operation $\bigvee$ above). Denote the subcategory of $\mathbf{PCstar}$ whose objects are partial AW*-algebras and whose morphisms are partial *-morphisms which preserve RP and $\bigvee$ by $\mathbf{PAWstar}$. ${}_{\blacksquare}$
Definition 32 The category $\mathbf{RingedTopos}$ has as objects pairs $(T,R)$ of a topos $T$ and an internal ring object $R\in T$. A morphism $(T,R)\to(T^{\prime},R^{\prime})$ consists of a geometric morphism $F\colon T^{\prime}\to T$ and an internal ring morphism $\varphi\colon R^{\prime}\to F^{*}(R)$ in $T$. By $\mathbf{CstaredTopos}$ we denote the subcategory of $\mathbf{RingedTopos}$ of objects $(T,A)$ where $A$ is an internal C*-algebra in $T$ and morphisms $(F,\varphi)$ where $\varphi$ is an internal *-ring morphism. ${}_{\blacksquare}$
Definition 11 A partial C*-algebra consists of a set $A$ with • a reflexive and symmetric binary (commeasurability) relation $\odot\subseteq A\times A$; • elements $0,1\in A$; • a (total) involution $*\colon A\to A$; • a (total) function $\cdot\colon\mathbb{C}\times A\to A$; • a (total) function $\left|\!\left|-\right|\!\right|:A\to\mathbb{R}$; • (partial) binary operations $+,\cdot\colon\odot\to A$; such that every set $S\subseteq A$ of pairwise commeasurable elements is contained in a set $T\subseteq A$, whose elements are also pairwise commeasurable, and on which the above operations determine the structure of a commutative C*-algebra.4This entails that $T$ contains 0 and 1, is closed under all algebraic operations, and is norm-complete. ${}_{\blacksquare}$
Definition 6 A partial complete Boolean algebra consists of a partial Boolean algebra together a (partial) operation $\bigvee\colon\{X\subseteq A\mid X\times X\subseteq\odot\}\to A$ such that every set $S\subseteq A$ of pairwise commeasurable elements is contained in a set $T\subseteq A$, whose elements are also pairwise commeasurable, and on which the above operations determine a complete Boolean algebra structure.3So $T$ is not only closed under $\lnot,\land$ and $\lor$, but also under $\bigvee$. A morphism of partial complete Boolean algebras is a function that preserves commeasurability and all the algebraic structure, including $\bigvee$, whenever defined. We write $\mathbf{PCBoolean}$ for the resulting category. ${}_{\blacksquare}$
Definition 12 A partial *-morphism is a (total) function $f\colon A\to B$ between partial C*-algebras such that: • $f(a)\odot f(b)$ for commeasurable $a,b\in A$; • $f(ab)=f(a)f(b)$ for commeasurable $a,b\in A$; • $f(a+b)=f(a)+f(b)$ for commeasurable $a,b\in A$; • $f(a+ib)=f(a)+if(b)$ for self-adjoint $a,b\in A$; • $f(za)=zf(a)$ for $z\in\mathbb{C}$ and $a\in A$; • $f(a)^{*}=f(a^{*})$ for $a\in A$; • $f(1)=1$. Partial C*-algebras and partial *-morphisms organize themselves into a category denoted by $\mathbf{PCstar}$.5Most results hold for nonunital C*-algebras, but for convenience we consider unital ones. ${}_{\blacksquare}$
Definition 1 A partial Boolean algebra consists of a set $A$ with • a reflexive and symmetric binary (commeasurability) relation $\odot\subseteq A\times A$; • elements $0,1\in A$; • a (total) unary operation $\lnot\colon A\to A$; • (partial) binary operations $\land,\lor\colon\odot\to A$; such that every set $S\subseteq A$ of pairwise commeasurable elements is contained in a set $T\subseteq A$, whose elements are also pairwise commeasurable, and on which the above operations determine a Boolean algebra structure.2Note that this means that $T$ must contain 0 and 1 and has to be closed under $\lnot,\land$ and $\lor$. A morphism of partial Boolean algebras is a function that preserves commeasurability and all the algebraic structure, whenever defined. We write $\mathbf{PBoolean}$ for the resulting category. ${}_{\blacksquare}$
Definition 29 Let $A$ and $B$ be a pair of partial Boolean algebras (partial C*-algebras). Define $A\otimes B=\mathop{\mathrm{colim}}\{C+D\mid C\in\mathcal{C}(A),D\in\mathcal{C}% (B)\},$ where $C+D$ is the coproduct in the category of Boolean algebras (commutative C*-algebras). ${}_{\blacksquare}$
