Definition 5. A flat $G$-connection is a functor $A:\Pi_{1}(B)\mathop{\rightarrow}G$ A gauge transformation $\alpha:A\mathop{\rightarrow}A^{\prime}$ from one connection to another is a natural transformation of functors so that $\alpha_{x}\in G$ satisfies $\alpha_{y}A(\gamma)=A^{\prime}(\gamma)\alpha_{x}$ for each path $\gamma:x\mathop{\rightarrow}y$. Flat connections and natural transformations form the objects and morphisms of the category $\mathcal{A}_{0}({B})_{G}=[\Pi_{1}(B),G]$
Definition 1. An $n$-dimensional Topological Quantum Field Theory is a (symmetric) monoidal functor $Z:\boldsymbol{\operatorname{{nCob}}}\mathop{\rightarrow}\boldsymbol{% \operatorname{{Vect}}}$ where is the monoidal category of $(n-1)$-dimensional manifolds and $n$-dimensional cobordisms, and $\boldsymbol{\operatorname{{Vect}}}$ is the monoidal category whose objects are vector spaces, whose arrows are linear transformations, and whose monoidal operation is the usual tensor product $\otimes$.
Definition 9. The monoidal 2-category $\operatorname{Span}(\boldsymbol{\operatorname{{Gpd}}})^{U(1)}$ has: • Objects: groupoids $A$ equipped with 2-cocycle $\theta\in Z^{2}(A,U(1)$ • 1-Morphisms: a morphism from $(A,\theta_{A})$ to $(B,\theta_{B})$ is a span of groupoids $A\stackrel{{\scriptstyle s}}{{\mathop{\leftarrow}}}X\stackrel{{\scriptstyle t}% }{{\mathop{\rightarrow}}}B$, equipped with 1-cocycle $\alpha\in Z^{1}(X,U(1))$ • 2-morphisms: a 2-morphism from $(X,\alpha,s,t)$ to $(X^{\prime},\alpha^{\prime},s^{\prime},t^{\prime})$ in $Hom((A,\theta_{A}),(B,\theta_{B}))$ is a class of spans of span maps $X\mathop{\leftarrow}Y\mathop{\rightarrow}X^{\prime}$ equipped with 0-cocycle $\beta\in Z^{0}(Y,U(1))$, with equivalence taken up to $\beta$-preserving isomorphism of $Y$ Subject to the conditions: • In any 1-morphism $(X,\alpha,s,t):(A,\theta_{A})\mathop{\rightarrow}(B,\theta_{B})$ the cocycles satisfy $(s^{\ast}\theta_{A})=(t^{\ast}\theta_{B})$ In particular, $[s^{\ast}\theta_{A}]=[t^{\ast}\theta_{B}]$ • In any 2-morphism $(Y,\beta,\sigma,\tau):(X_{1},\alpha_{1},s_{1},t_{1})\Rightarrow(X_{2},\alpha_{% 2},s_{2},t_{2})$ the cocycles satisfy $(\sigma^{\ast}\alpha_{1})(\tau^{\ast}\alpha_{2})^{-1}=1$ (In particular, $[\sigma^{\ast}\alpha_{1}]=[\tau^{\ast}\alpha_{2}]$, but moreover, since a 0-cocycle on a groupoid is an invariant function, $\delta\beta=0$ and the cocycles themselves are equal.) The structures making $\operatorname{Span}(\boldsymbol{\operatorname{{Gpd}}})^{U(1)}$ a monoidal 2-category are: • Composition of 1-morphisms $(X_{1},\alpha_{1},s_{1},t_{1}):(A,\theta_{A})\mathop{\rightarrow}(B,\theta_{B})$ and $(X_{2},\alpha_{2},s_{2},t_{2}):(B,\theta_{B})\mathop{\rightarrow}(C,\theta_{C})$ at the object $(B,\theta_{B})$ gives the same span of groupoids as in $\operatorname{Span}(\boldsymbol{\operatorname{{Gpd}}})$, and assigns the pullback object the cocycle $\alpha_{1}\cdot\alpha_{2}\cdot\theta_{B}$ (explained below) • Vertical composition of 2-morphisms: $(Y,\beta,\sigma,\tau):(X_{1},\alpha_{1},s_{1},t_{1})\mathop{\rightarrow}(X_{2}% ,\alpha_{2},s_{2},t_{2})$ and $(Y^{\prime},\beta^{\prime},\sigma^{\prime},\tau^{\prime}):(X_{2},\alpha_{2},s_% {2},t_{2})\mathop{\rightarrow}(X_{3},\alpha_{3},s_{3},t_{3})$ at $(X_{2},\alpha_{2})$ gives the same groupoids as in $\operatorname{Span}(\boldsymbol{\operatorname{{Gpd}}})$, with the cocycle given by $\beta\cdot\beta^{\prime}\cdot\alpha_{2}$ • Horizontal composition of 2-morphisms: $(Y,\beta,\sigma,\tau):(X_{1},\alpha_{1},s_{1},t_{1})\mathop{\rightarrow}(X_{2}% ,\alpha_{2},s_{2},t_{2})$ in $Hom((A,\theta_{A}),(B,\theta_{B}))$, and $(Y^{\prime},\beta^{\prime},\sigma^{\prime},\tau^{\prime}):(X_{1}^{\prime},% \alpha_{1}^{\prime},s_{1}^{\prime},t_{1}^{\prime})\mathop{\rightarrow}(X_{2}^{% \prime},\alpha_{2}^{\prime},s_{2}^{\prime},t_{2}^{\prime})$ in $Hom((B,\theta_{B}),(C,\theta_{C}))$ at $(B,\theta_{B})$ gives the same groupoids as in $\operatorname{Span}(\boldsymbol{\operatorname{{Gpd}}})$, with the cocycle given by $\beta\cdot\beta^{\prime}\cdot\theta_{B}$ • The monoidal structure is given by $(A,\theta_{A})\otimes(B,\theta_{B})=(A\times B,\theta_{A}\cdot\theta_{B})$
